[4] USA (North Carolina)
Date: Fri 15 Dec 2017
Source: Citizen Times [edited]
http://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/local/2017/12/15/henderson-county-whooping-cough-cases-double-week/955425001/


The number of reported whooping cough cases in Henderson County more than doubled in the past week, rising from 21 cases on 8 Dec. 2017 to 45 cases on Friday [15 Dec 2017] according to the Department of Public Health. Henderson County has been fighting to contain the outbreak of whooping cough, known formally as pertussis, since the 1st case was reported in mid-November 2017 at Hillandale Elementary School, about 4.5 miles southeast of downtown Hendersonville.

In the month since, the respiratory infection has spread beyond the schools and is impacting the community at large. As of 8 Dec 2017, more than 1000 people in Henderson County had been in close contact with somebody with whooping cough, which is "easily spread when someone with the infection coughs or sneezes," according to a press release from Henderson County.

No cases of whooping cough have been reported in Buncombe County, according to Dr. Jennifer Mullendore, medical director at the Department of Health and Human Services. Anybody, including people who have been vaccinated, can contract whooping cough though the symptoms may be milder for those with vaccinations. The infection is particularly dangerous for infants, pregnant women and anyone with a compromised immune system.

[Byline: Sam DeGrave]

--
Communicated by:
