[5] Michigan
Date: Fri 15 Dec 2017
Source: WLNS [edited]
http://wlns.com/2017/12/15/confirmed-case-of-whooping-cough-at-grand-ledge-public-schools/


Grand Ledge Public Schools [GLPS] has confirmed cases of pertussis, also known as whooping cough. In a letter released Friday [15 Dec 2017] through social media, school officials confirmed the cases.

"If there's one infection in the school and the kid is not properly been diagnosed for it, potential is there for him to go, or her to go and continue to infect other kids," says Sparrow Urgent Care Physician, Song Yu. Yu says whooping cough can be a very serious illness, especially in young children. "We recommend treatment within the 1st 7-10 days; the problem is though until you get the symptoms that are obvious, you're not going to have that until week 2 or 3," says Yu.

The administrator at Grand Ledge Public Schools released a letter stating there have been confirmed cases of the disease in the school system. That letter asked parents to get their students vaccinated before entering kindergarten and to keep children at home if they show any signs of the illness.

Although most children are given the vaccine for whooping cough during routine childhood immunizations, booster doses are required over time. GLPS is working with the Barry/Eaton Health Department, and they ask you to check your child's immunization records. If your child has not been protected against this illness, it is recommended that you go to your doctor to have them immunized. If you have any questions about the issue, you can contact the Barry/Eaton District Health Department. For more information, visit http://www.cdc.gov/feature/pertussis.

